sql:
SELECT title, original_title
FROM movies
WHERE revenue > (SELECT AVG(revenue) FROM movies);

external_knowledge:
- The metaphorical terms like "vineyard," "sprout," "seed," "tangled," "tangled vineyard of cinematic connections," "fertile soil," "cinematic fruits," "unravel," "hierarchy of these vines," "lush harvest," and "pluck the richest three genres from the garden" refer to the complex relationships and hierarchy established between movies and genres based on their titles and revenue generation; 
- The "top revenue-generating genres" refers to the genres that have generated the highest total revenue; 
- "Hierarchy of these vines" refers to the order of movies related via their titles; 
- "Lush harvest" represents the total revenue associated with each genre; 
- "Nurturing" here means the genres that support or produce these movies based on the hierarchical relationship.

Profitability tiers signify different segments based on the profit quartiles; revenue ranks reflect the standing of movies based on their revenue rankings. Both analyses help in understanding the distribution and average financial performance across different segments.;
Quartiles divide the data into four equal parts, each representing 25% of the data set.; 
Ranks order the movies based on the revenue, showing which movies stand out in terms of financial success.

sql:
SELECT title, AVG(vote_average) AS average_rating
FROM movies
GROUP BY title;

external_knowledge:
- Cinematic voyages refer to the titles of movies;
- Realms they sail through refers to the genres the movies belong to;
- Vessels that float in each ocean refers to the count of movies in each genre.

sql:
SELECT title
FROM movies
ORDER BY release_date DESC;

external_knowledge:
- 'flicks' refers to movies;
- 'most popular' is determined by the popularity score of movies;
- 'top ten' means the highest 10 ranks when movies are ranked by their popularity scores.

- "sea of cinema" refers to the collection of movies; "past decade" indicates the time range from 2010 to 2020;
- "financial voyage" is a metaphor for the economic performance of a movie;
- "ship based on its journey stage" reflects the production status of a movie, denoting the phase of its development and preparation for release;
- "lighthouse" metaphorically represents the insight provided by the average budget and revenue, guiding understanding and decisions.

